fields.beacon_bio: I'm a Franco-American, oldest of five, and proud Cal graduate. I am exciting to be starting my career as a physician-scientist, and will be doing research in regenerative medicine and tissue engineering.

BioEHS Involvement: Outreach, TM (Junior/Senior Chair), Treasurer, Senior Advisor
Original career aspiration: MD
Actual path: Decided in 3rd year to attend PhD for a number of factors, largely stemmed from interest in research projects instead
Background: devices (electrochemical and visual/fluorescence sensors), drug delivery polymer system, microfabrication
I will be applying for graduate school in 2020. I plan to go into a synthetic biology or microbiology program.

I'm a BioEECS double that came into Cal knowing I wanted to go to grad school; from there, everything more or less fell into place -- I got involved in BioEHSC™, which only served to confirm my interest in helping inspire the next generation of researchers. The best way to do this is as a PI at a university, which leads me to where I am now.

I recently started working for Thermo Fisher Scientific as a part of their Operations Leadership Development Program. This is entirely different than what I pursued at Berkeley - where I studied Bioengineering (Bioimaging concentration) & EECS, got a design innovation certificate, and completed all the pre-reqs for being pre-med. After deciding against pre-med, feeling hesitant about a PhD/ full-time roles, I looked into rotational programs and fell into my current role!

I had transferred to UC Berkeley from Rio Hondo College in Los Angeles in 2016 with the intention of becoming a Bioengineer. While the process was tumultuous I eventually achieved position in a synthetic biology that I would become fond of.

Hi BioEHS! I transferred to UC Berkeley Bioengineering from a community college and joined BioEHS immediately once I got on campus. Within BioEHS, I was the ProDev Chair and EVP. I helped set up some of the BioTech Connect events when BioEHS first started co-hosting these events. I also helped organize the 4th BioEHSC(TM).
I was originally interested in orthopedics but I shifted to medical devices and started a career in electronic medical devices while using my Japanese language skills.

Hi! My name is Nikko and I am currently a Ph.D. student in Engineering Sciences at Harvard University. Coming to Berkeley, research has always been a fleeting interest of mine; I soon realized that pursuing a Ph.D. was something that I really wanted to do after working in Prof. Healy's lab. At Harvard, I work in Prof. Mooney's lab for Cell and Tissue Engineering. Here, I am trying to figure out a way to mechanically reprogram T-Cells for applications in immunoengineering and immunotherapy.

I originally came into bioengineering interested in stem cells but as years passed grew interested in a variety of fields including rapid diagnostics/microfluidics, synthetic biology, cell/tissue engineering, therapeutics, etc. I considered pre-med very briefly before deciding not to go down that path. I didn't think I would go into industry, but here I am, after 4 years, going in industry haha! I'm planning on working for a few years and potentially going to grad school after.

I am currently pursuing an academic career studying the neuroscience of language learning. The defining trait of my life up to this point, however, has been an interest in (and desire to do) anything and everything. As an undergrad I focused in Synth & Comp Biology, education (as a UGSI & SLC tutor), and outreach (with BioEHS, GBO, and other orgs). Feel free to reach out if you have questions about any of my experiences, or if you just want to talk about figuring out where to go in life!

I am currently a PhD student at UCLA in Bioengineering. I am doing research in cell and tissue engineering with a focus on regenerative medicine. I originally was interested in industry and still am, but I am going to grad school before going to industry.

fields.notes: This is a test to see if notes will appear.

fields.beacon_bio: My name is Shilpi, and I am a masters student in the Master of Engineering program in bioengineering. I also completed my undergrad here at Berkeley! I've been involved with BioEHS since my sophomore year. Though I have explored my options of being pre-med, going into industry, and going to grad school, I have ultimately chosen the path to do my masters. Future goals include working in industry and becoming a project manager. Feel free to add me on Facebook or shoot me an email!

While at Berkeley, I was an active BioEHS member and officer; participating in both internal and external committees. During my junior year, I was a researcher in a UCSC microfluidics lab and quickly decided that traditional academia was not my calling. During my senior year, I was totally engulfed in my internship at Intuitive Surgical and quickly converted to a full-time contractor after graduation. At Intuitive, I lead several user studies and contributed to the development of the da Vinci Si and and da Vinci Xi simulation systems. I am currently slated to attend the UCSD School of Medicine in August 2014 and can't wait to practice my engineering mentality in a medical setting.
My name is Darena. I am originally from Thailand before coming to the US. I enjoy going outdoors, trying new restaurants, and sleeping. I was also a former officer for BioEHS.

I moved from Thailand in 2001. I went to middle/high school in SoCal. I originally was in undeclared L&S major and applied for BioE in my Sophomore year. I currently work at Boehringer Ingelheim, a German based biopharmaceutical company located in Fremont. I used to work in the Purification Manufacturing plant, ranging from 2000L to 12000L harvest scale, but I am now in Process Science department, doing monoclonal antibody purification development work.

I write and edit for BioCentury Publications, the leading source of news and analysis for the biotech industry. We cover the formation, development and sustainability of life science ventures and the major strategic issues that impact this ecosystem.

I am a fourth year medical student at UCLA applying into Otolaryngology, aka Head and Neck Surgery aka ENT. I am happy to talk to or chat with anyone considering a career in medicine. I love tissue engineering and have been working on projects growing different types of tissue including vocal folds! I hope my biotech interests play a large role in my future career as a practicing surgeon.

I am (hopefully) on the verge of finishing my PhD in bioengineering by using microfluidics to revolutionize the way we treat cancer. My plan after graduating is to jump into the start-up life, working to commercialize my tech. As a past BioEHS prez, I am happy to help out! Also, my professor (Dino Di Carlo) was supposedly one of the first members.

I graduated UC Berkeley in 2011 within the Pre-med track and then immediately matriculated into New York Medical College for medical school. I am currently a 4th year medical student and I will be matching into Internal Medicine with interests in a Pulmonary/Critical Care fellowship.

- 2 years research in the Rine Lab studying yeast genetics (2011 Amgen Scholar) - Worked for 1/2 year at Amyris on biologically derived drop-in jet fuels - Current PhD student in the Church Lab at Harvard Medical School.

Management consultant in McKinsey and Company at their San Francisco office and Operations Practice. Previously an Analyst in the Abbott operations leadership rotational program. Masters in Management Science and Engineering from Stanford, Bachelors in Bioengineering from UC Berkeley, and plans to start MBA at Harvard. Ex-premed with a passion for food and music.

Hi, I am Libing! I graduated from Cal in 2012. There, I took a range of classes from the Cell and Tissue Engineering, Biomedical Devices, and Pre-med concentrations. I was also a BioEHS officer from 2009 until 2012 and I love BioEHS members!

I majored in Chemical engineering with minors in bioengineering and data science. I started college wanting to go straight to work after graduation, but as I did internships and undergrad research, I figured out that grad school was a better fit for me. So I’m here now at Stanford working towards a PhD in chemical engineering

Incoming Master of Engineering student at UC Berkeley focusing on Bioengineering with a concentration in Biomedical Design Engineering, along with a strong interest in Business Administration. Passionate about CAR-T Cell related immuno-oncology therapeutics, small/large molecule drug discovery and delivery, and CRISPR-based gene technologies. Actively participated in research at the Conboy's lab for more than two years. Expertise lies in cancer proteomics and microarray analytics.

I started as a pre-med BioE, but discovered that I also enjoyed CS. I decided to pursue the BioE/EECS double major because I was interested in the intersection of software and biotechnology/healthcare. I considered a PhD but felt I hadn't figured out my interests enough for the commitment. I instead went into industry, where I'm at an early stage (<10 people) startup doing machine learning for healthcare. My current plan is to do grad school after, for either an MBA or PhD in machine learning.
